Korea-Bulgarian Summit on Cooperation in Nuclear Power Plants and Defense Industries (Bulgarian) | Yahoo!
(SEOUL=Yonhap News) South Korean President Moon Jae-in held a meeting with Bulgaria's Prime Minister Borisov during his official visit to Korea on September 27 to discuss ways to expand bilateral cooperation.
This was the first time the Prime Minister of Bulgaria visited Korea.
President Moon welcomed the visit to Korea before the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations next year, and appreciated the leadership of Prime Minister Borisov, who led the development of Bulgaria.
The two leaders appreciated the continued increase in trade and investment between the two countries amid the expansion of protectionist tradeism globally, and agreed to work together to expand economic cooperation in the future.
President Moon welcomed Bulgaria's policy to grant Korean companies the status of "strategic investors," and said he hoped that this would help Korean companies invest in Bulgaria.
He also emphasized that Korea would be the best partner for Bulgaria in the process of introducing nuclear power plants and modernizing defense, and called for attention and cooperation so that Korean companies could participate in the order of the Bulgarian government's nuclear power plants and the promotion of the defense industry.
In addition, the two leaders agreed to strengthen future-oriented cooperation in the areas of battery and auto parts for electric vehicles and renewable energy.
Prime Minister Borisov hoped that Korea's leading ICT (information and communication technology) and science, technology, and education sectors would cooperate closely.
They also discussed the peace process on the Korean Peninsula, and President Moon expressed his gratitude for the Government of Korea's support for the efforts of the Korean government to establish peace on the Korean Peninsula, including Bulgaria's announcement of a statement supporting the North-South and US-North Korea Summit.
Prime Minister Borisov appreciated President Moon's will to build a peace regime on the Korean Peninsula and the efforts of the Korean government, and reiterated the firm support of the Bulgarian government.
The meeting was attended by Jo Yunmo, Secretary of the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy, Lee Hao-houn, Chief Secretary of the Economic Affairs Bureau of the President's Office, and Kim Hyun-jong, Second Director of the National Security Office.
The first secretary of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Zhao Se-yong, also attended the meeting.
Local industry in Hyogo and Awaji Island, Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd., which manufactures "Awaji tiles," filed for quasi-self-insolvency debt of approximately 2 billion yen (Imperial Data Bank) - Yahoo!
It was also affected by the sluggish housing market and the frequent damage caused by the earthquake that "consumer tile roofs were removed."
Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd. (TDB Corporation Code: 530173983; capital of 9.92 million yen; 881-8 Otani, Awaji City, Hyogo Prefecture; representative Yukizo Fukuhara; 44 employees) filed for quasi-self-insolvency at the Kobe District Court on August 30.
The applicant is Daichi Yoshida (1-10-8 Nishitenman, Kita Ward, Osaka City, Osaka Prefecture), and one other attorney.
The company was founded in June 1895 and reorganized as a corporation in April 1961.
At first, he started his business as a manufacturer of ibushi tiles, a local industry in Awaji Island, in Nishitan-cho, Mihara County (present Minamiawaji City) under the trade name of Kinki Kiln Co., Ltd.
In October 1986, Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd. merged with Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd. to succeed the business of Kinki Sangyo Co., Ltd., and at the same time, the head office was relocated to its present location after changing its present business name.
After that, sales offices were established in Fukuyama City, Hiroshima City, Oita City, Miyazaki City, etc., and it became the current system, and Ibushi-gawara was mainly used before, but due to changes in consumer needs, Western-style tiles such as flat plate tiles were manufactured at 70%, and Ibushi-gawara was manufactured at 30%.
The company has established a wide range of sales bases mainly in western Japan, including major house manufacturers, construction materials trading companies, and roof construction companies.
He was well known as the top tile maker of Awaji Island.
However, due to the sluggish housing market following the Lehman shock and the frequent damage caused by the Great East Japan Earthquake and the Kumamoto Earthquake, demand for tiled roofs has been sluggish, and annual sales for the fiscal year ended December 2018 were down to approximately 1.345 million yen.
In terms of profits, in addition to a decline in profit margin due to the surge in fuel prices, the company suffered a continuous deficit due to excessive interest-bearing debt associated with inventory burdens and business fixed investment, and was forced to carry out severe financing.
For this reason, the Bank tried to rebuild its business by requesting financial institutions to ease the conditions for repayment of loans, but there were no signs of recovery in business conditions, and financial conditions were gradually tight.
He was unable to support the project and gave up on continuing the business.
The debt is currently under investigation, but it is estimated to be about 2 billion yen.
Prefectural Dinosaur Museum in Katsuyama City, Fukui Prefecture, which promotes the industrialization of tourism (photographed by Japanese aerial photographs and small drones)
Katsuyama City, Fukui Prefecture, announced on September 25 that it will acquire approximately 25,000 square meters of land adjacent to the construction site of the road station "Dinosaur Valley Katsuyama," which will open next spring.
In order to accelerate the "industrialization of tourism" advocated by the city and the local economy, we aim to attract accommodation-specific hotels and restaurants.
On the same day, the board members explained at the Special Committee for the Improvement of the City Council's Invitational Base.
With the opening of the Hokuriku Shinkansen in the spring of 2023, as well as the opening of the entire section of the Chubu Jukan Expressway within the prefecture, as well as the expansion and renovation of the Prefectural Dinosaur Museum (Katsuyama City), the city intends to promote a shift from day-trip center to stay-style sightseeing, and attract accommodation.
It is a private idle land next to the east of the road station construction site.
Surrounded by the Kuzuryu River, Takinami River and the prefectural road, it is more than twice the size of a roadside station (about 12,000 square meters).
In the name of the industrial complex development, the City Land Development Corporation will proceed with land negotiations from this year, acquire land, and build land in FY21.
According to the city, private businesses such as farmers' restaurants and harvest experience facilities, fast food, and restaurants are already looking to enter the market.
As for accommodation, it was also revealed that Sekisui House has promoted the name of the city to attract accommodation-specific hotels adjacent to Michi No Eki, which is planned throughout Japan.
Sekisui House is planning to expand into three locations within Fukui Prefecture, but there are also several other cities and towns that are willing to attract and may compete.
The city also plans to build a parking lot.
