"I hope Korea will return to GSOMIA." - Yahoo!
U.S. Under-Secretary of the U.S. Under-Secretary of the U.S. Under-Secretary for South Korea and Japan, Mr. Napper, in an interview with the Sankei Shimbun at the residence of the U.S. Ambassador to the United States in Tokyo, said on November 27 that he hoped that Korea would reconsider and return the decision to destroy Japan and Korea's comprehensive military information protection agreement
It is unusual for senior U.S. officials to refer to the reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, South Korea, the United States, the United States, and South Korea to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
Napper argued that "without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to crises."
He strongly urged the return of Korea, saying, "There is time until revocation."
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted by China and Russia over the Sea of Japan in July was the first time in history. He said, "It is essential that the United States, Korea and Japan, which share values such as democracy and human rights, collaborate in alliance relations."
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damaged the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "Japan and Korea will play a positive role to fill the gap."
