Koichi Soda (64), an artist in the Echizen City Regional Revitalization Cooperation Team in Fukui Prefecture, started a crowdfunding campaign aimed at publishing creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture in order to promote town development using picture books.
Mr. Soda, who was originally from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group in April this year, says, "I want to convey the hearts of the people of Fukui based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey the heart of Fukui.
While Mr. Soda is active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, he has also been active as a member of the cooperative team since the end of the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he moved to Echizen City in April this year.
The city, which produced Riko Kako and Chihiro IWASAKI, aims to create a town using picture books.
Mr. Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion around me for the first time."
I focused on the legend of the city of Awara, 'The face of the demon of the bride'.
It is a story that a gentle married woman continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother without worrying about the fact that she was surprised by her face.
"I forgot my hatred, returned with kindness and kindness, and felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived, and completed the story "Meoto Oni" where a loving couple and a boy appear.
From June, he drew 10 scenes with warm watercolors, taking advantage of his job, and the materials of picture books were scattered.
In addition, the cover of picture books will be made with washi using Echizen Washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City.
This leads to an opportunity for parents and children to enjoy the touch of Japanese paper by reading and listening.
The goal of the donation amount is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is 25 October.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to tell children what true kindness and compassion are handed down through picture books."
