Okayama Art Exchange Opens in the City Center: Sanyo Newspaper Digital|Sanyo Digital
People around the classroom, the setting of a video work depicting the future 3,000 years later
The international art exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" (organized by the executive committee of the city, prefecture, etc.) held every three years in central Okayama City opened on the 27th.
Along with the mysterious title "IF THE SNAKE If Snake," 18 artists from 9 countries enjoy cutting-edge art.
This time, the second time since 16 years, we have invited French artist Pierre Yuig as artistic director to develop works that utilize Okayama's climate and local resources.
Approximately 40 films and three-dimensional works will be shown at 13 locations including the former Uchiyama Shimoko (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City) and the prefectural Tenjinyama Cultural Plaza (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City).
Prior to the opening ceremony, a small opening ceremony was held, and about 100 people attended.
Mayor Masao Omori, executive producer Yasuharu Ishikawa, and other members of the executive committee said, "The works that stimulate intellectual sensibilities and stimulate imagination and creativity have come together, and it will become an exhibition that attracts attention from the world."
Families and children studying outside the school immediately visited the school and found a snake-shaped robot that responds to the surrounding sounds in the dohyo of the schoolyard, and walked around the school building, which turned into a stage for a video work depicting the world 3,000 years later.
I enjoyed the art that led to different worlds.
While traveling with my father, a first-year high school student in Tokyo (15) said, "It's interesting to make use of the atmosphere of the old school building, and I can imagine the time that flows into this place."
It is closed on November 24 (the following day if it is a national holiday).
Meeting in Hong Kong, 5 years of the Umbrella Movement tens of thousands, aiming for a general election | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Five years have passed since the "Umbrella Movement" began, and the people gathered at the meeting venue = 28th, Hong Kong (joint)
[Collaboration with Hong Kong] On the 28th of May 2014, a large-scale demonstration called the "Umbrella Movement," which sought democratization of the election of the Hong Kong Secretary of State, was held in a park near the Hong Kong Government Headquarters building of the Admiralty, which had its largest base.
Some young people occupied the main road around the venue and threw a flame bottle at the government office.
As protests started with the amendment of the Fugitive Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their determination to fight until the realization of a "true ordinary election" that could not be won at the time.
In June, more than 79 days after the Umbrella Movement, 112 days of protests began, and the demands of the demonstrators expanded to "five major demands" such as electoral reform.
